<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS -- About 600 Nigerian soldiers arrived in Lagos on board
a naval vessel Friday, as Nigeria is carrying out a four-phased
withdrawal of its troops from the west African peace-keeping force
in Liberia known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Before them, about 1,200 soldiers had returned from Monrovia on
December 20, 1997. ECOMOG, under the control of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), has been in Liberia
since 1990, when a civil war broke out there.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional peace-keeping force has been given the
deadline of February 2 to pull out by Liberian president Charles
Taylor. (Nigeria-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A 22-man international team of weapons experts
arrived in Baghdad Saturday for talks designed to iron out
differences between Iraq and United Nations weapons inspectors,
Iraqi news agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
Husam Mohammed Ameen, director general of Iraqi National
Monitoring Directorate, the Iraqi peer of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM on disarmament in Iraq) said that missile
warhead experts would start their five-day technical evaluation
meetings Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A second group of adepts at chemical VX agent is scheduled to
arrive here Sunday and start meetings with Iraqi officials
Monday. Those meetings are to be concluded on February 6, said
Ameen. (Iraq-International Team-Arrival)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAVOS, Switzerland -- It is no time for protectionism when the
world has encountered a financial crisis, World Trade Organization
(WTO) Director-General Renato Ruggiero told reporters here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in the Congress Center, the site of the
annual meeting of the World Economic Forum, Ruggiero urged the
United States and Europe to keep their markets open in order to
help stabilize international financial situation.
(Switzerland-WTO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
