<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Wastes 4 Billion Dollars in Energy annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Annual energy waste in Iran
stands at 7,000 billion Rials (4 billion U.S. dollars), the
Persian daily Iran reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Automobiles and factories are the major sources of the waste,
Mohammad Rahmati, director general for energy affairs of the
Planning and Budget Organization, told the daily.
</P>
<P>
The world standard energy consumption for a car is 4-5 liters
of fuel for 100 kilometers, while the figure in Iran is 10-25
liters, he said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the high consumption of energy, Iran wastes nine dollars
for producing one tonne of steel and 100 dollars for producing one
tonne of aluminum, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran is one of the countries with the highest level of
energy waste in the world.
</P>
<P>
This phenomenon has set off serious concern of Iranian
officials, who have warned that the country will have to stop
exporting oil in 15 years with the current energy consumption
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
An official said earlier this month that Iran's daily fuel
consumption had increased by about 200 percent to 1.5 million
barrels of oil from 509,000 barrels during the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Iran's proven oil reserve stands at 93 billion barrels. It is
allowed by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Counties to
produce 3.94 million barrels per day, of which 2.5 million barrels
are exported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
