<HEADLINE> Gaullist RPR Holds Conference to Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 31 (Xinhua) -- France's Gaullist movement, the
Rally for the Republic (RPR), began a two-day conference Saturday
aimed at adopting a new political project to adapt the party to
the evolving political situation at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In a message sent to the conference, President Jacques Chirac,
who is from the RPR, said that France "needs more than ever the
ideals of the Gaullist movement."
</P>
<P>
He called on RPR politicians to rally behind its new president,
former parliament speaker Philippe Seguin, a hawk in confronting
the Socialist-led majority and the government of Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Seguin accused Prime Minister Jospin of
"not governing but wavering" in his social and economic policy.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Figaro, which is the mouthpiece for the RPR, said
that Gaullist militants will promote the idea of economic
liberalism and a free and dynamic economy in France, which they
think is the only way to tackle unemployment and guarantee social
cohesion in the face of economic globalization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
