<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-31 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Pilgrims Visit Mosque in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 31 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,280 Turkish
Cypriots Saturday crossed the Green Line into the
government-controlled south for a pilgrimage to Hala Sultan Tekke
Mosque in Larnaca on the southeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
Around 28 buses, provided by the Greek Cypriot side, took
the Turkish Cypriots to the Hala Sultan Tekke to celebrate Eid
El-Fitr, marking the end of the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
The Hala Sultan Tekke, located on the shore of Larnaca's Salt
Lake, was built in memory of Umm Haram, an aunt of Prophet
Mohammed and is considered one of the holiest Islamic Shrines.
</P>
<P>
Last year Turkish Cypriots were also allowed on several
occasions to cross the U.N.-controlled Greek Line to visit the
Turkish Cypriot enclave of Kokkina, in the northeastern part of
the island, and pay a pilgrimage to Hala Sultan Tekke mosque
in Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,650 Greek Cypriot pilgrims were also permitted
on two occasions to visit the Apostolos Andreas Monastery, at
the Turkish-controlled eastern tip of the island.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits was agreed upon by Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash during
their meetings in Nicosia Earlier last year.
</P>
<P>
This East Mediterranean island has been divided into Greek
Cypriot-dominated south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
People from the two sides have been prohibited to cross
the 180-kilometer-long U.N.-controlled buffer zone which separates
the island into two parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
