<HEADLINE> Somali Factions Reach Agreement on Opening Air, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The Somali factions meeting
here on Saturday have reached an agreement on opening air and
seaports in Mogadishu and the abolishing of all the green lines
that bisected the capital in the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which took place at Hotel Kah at Yaqahid district
was attended by nearly one hundred politicians, traditional
leaders and religious scholars led by Ali Mahdi Mohamed, Hussein
Mohamed Aidid and Osman Ali Atto.
</P>
<P>
Outside the hotel were thousands of cheering people and dozens
of technical vehicles from all sides waiting for the outcome of
the meeting and eager for a peaceful settlement in the capital.
</P>
<P>
As the meeting was concluded in the afternoon, the faction
leaders held a joint press conference which was attended by local
and international media representatives.
</P>
<P>
On the security issue, Ali Mahdi said at the press conference
that all armed clan militiamen will be demobilized into
designated camps and a collective security force with one
commanding center will soon be formed to safeguard the security
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
"Mogadishu should be unified and pacified in every sense in a
common administrative body very soon," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Mohamed Aidid said that the pacification of the
capital and the formation of a common administration for
Mogadishu is key to the Baidoa National Reconciliation Conference
due to be held in mid February for the formation of a government
of national unity.
</P>
<P>
According to Junior Aidid, a long lasting solution is in the
reach of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of the air and seaports of the capital will also
facilitate the international efforts in helping the flood, famine
and diseases stricken communities of Somalia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Osman Ali Atto stressed that no more words are
remained, but work.
</P>
<P>
"We now crossed to the stage of the implementation for the
Cairo meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
The faction leaders have also invited 30 members from each of
the Hawiye clans to attend the one-day conference on Monday at
the same hotel.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were a large delegation from the
Egyptian government led by Mohamud Mustafa, the Egyptian
ambassador to Somalia, and representatives from the Arab league
who are observatory guests.
</P>
<P>
This has been the first such meeting held jointly by
Mogadishu's politicians after the Cairo meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
