<HEADLINE> UK, US Imminent for Fundamental Decisions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Britain and the United States
warned Iraq today that all options, including the use of military
force, remained open if it did not comply with U.N. weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The message came after U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook met in London.
Albright flew into London from Madrid earlier today to consult
with her British counterpart on the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a joint news conference with Albright after their
meeting, Cook said the time was nearing for "fundamental decisions
to be made."
</P>
<P>
Albright said the two countries "stood shoulder to shoulder"
over the crisis, which she said was very grave.
</P>
<P>
"The window is narrowing.... It looks as if diplomacy is not
working," Albright added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state, on a mission to Europe and the
Middle East to win support for possible U.S. strikes on Iraq,
later left for Israel and for talks with Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Albright warned, "We further agreed that the only standard for
a real diplomatic solution is full Iraqi compliance with the
Security Council and unconditional, unfettered access for UNSCOM
(arms inspectors)."
</P>
<P>
The deepening row between Iraq and the United Nations hinges on
Baghdad's dispute with inspectors searching for documents and
materials related to its weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors have said they are convinced Iraq, which has
blocked them from eight "presidential sites," is concealing
evidence. But Iraq argues it has no nuclear, chemical or
biological weapons or ballistic missiles banned under terms of the
cease-fire ending the 1991 Gulf War in which U.S.-led forces drove
Iraqi troops out of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
