<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta on Alert Against Alleged ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has ordered all security personnel in the west of the
country, including the capital Freetown, to be on the alert.
</P>
<P>
The announcement, made by the Defense Department broadcast
first by the State Radio Friday night, gave no reason for the
move, the British Broadcasting Corporation reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, there has been speculation of possible military
strike against the junta by the west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But a junta spokesman said Saturday that the move was made
"because of the latest development that Nigeria is now resorting
to terrorism".
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigerian soldiers serving in ECOMOG based
near Freetown have abducted a number of members of a Guinean
delegation which is on a fact-finding mission in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The people were abducted on a highway on the way back to their
own country, he alleged.
</P>
<P>
But so far no protest has been heard from Guinea over the
abduction of its citizens in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The military government would not be afraid of anything
Nigeria can do to it, the spokesman said, adding the crisis in
the country could only be settled through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that Nigeria, which is reported to be the core
of ECOMOG, and ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah were going to
use force for the final resolution of the Sierra Leone crisis,
disregarding the existing peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord signed last October in Conakry, Guinea, the
junta is to hand over power to Kabbah on April 22. But the junta
leader, Johnny Paul Koroma, has said the deadline is unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
Both the United Nations and west African countries, which have
imposed sanctions against the junta, are opposed to the change of
the deadline, and the former is to send military observers to the
country to monitor the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the civil defense group loyal to Kabbah, known as
the Kamajors, have been fighting for the restoration of the
ousted president in the eastern part of the country bordering
Liberia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
