<HEADLINE> UAE Optimistic About Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates has
expressed optimism about the oil prices, the WAM news agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Oil and Mineral Resources of the UAE Obeid bin Saif
Al-Nasir told the WAM that he believed the world oil market will
recover after months of slump.
</P>
<P>
Al-Nasir's remarks came when world oil prices climbed to 16-17
dollars a barrel in the last four days from the lowest level of
14.78 dollars a barrel in 45 months.
</P>
<P>
Most oil-rich Gulf countries have based their 1998 budget on an
oil price at 16-17 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the concern about a military
confrontation between the United States and Iraq, which would
disrupt Iraq's oil export, led to the increase of the oil price.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has threatened to launch a military strike to force
Iraqi compliance with the United Nations Security Council
resolutions on the elimination of its weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
