<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-31 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Negotiations to End Iraqi-UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan Saturday called on the
concerned parties to end the crisis of arms inspection in Iraq
through negotiations rather than military confrontation, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has insisted that the crisis between Iraq and the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) be settled by negotiation, not
confrontation, to save the Iraqi people from tragedy and death,
Jordanian Minister of Foreign Affairs Fayez Tarawneh told the
Petra.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has expressed hope that negotiations and international
efforts would also help the UNSCOM exercise its mission without
any breach of Iraq's national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM is to certify the elimination of Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction before the U.N. Security Council can lift the
sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred UNSCOM's inspectors from searching for the
banned weapons in presidential palaces for the reasons of national
security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
And the United States has threatened to launch a military
strike to force Iraqi compliance with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's policy is based on the principle of solving conflicts
through "peaceful means and dialogue" instead of "resorting to the
language of destruction," the Jordanian foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the concerned parties to continue "diplomatic
efforts" to implement the U.N. Security Council resolutions,
which he said would help avoid "dangerous escalation" of the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
