<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Exports Increase in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's exports
earnings rose to 81.5 million U.S. dollars in last December,
respresenting an increase of 12.6 percent over the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report, the Bank of Tanzania (BoT) said that
the earnings from traditional exports went up 31.2 percent, while
earnings from non-traditional exports increased 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In December, earnings from the exports of most traditional
products increased in terms of both volume and prices, the BoT
said, with an exception of sisal, whose exports volume declined
by 76 percent.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional export earnings increased from 23.8 million US
dollars in November to 24.8 million US dollars in December.
</P>
<P>
The increase has been attributed to high export earnings from
petroleum products, manufactured goods and other exports.
</P>
<P>
"Minerals, cotton, yarn, fish and fish produce, manufactured
tabacco and horticulture products recorded lower earnings when
compared with their respective receipts in the previous months, "
says the bank report.
</P>
<P>
However, when comparison is made between the December of 1997
and the corresponding period in the previous year, earnings of
traditional exports and non-traditional exports dropped 13.7
percent and 29.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in earnings from traditional and non-traditional
products has been caused by heavy rains which have played havoc
with both crops and transportation network.
</P>
<P>
On annual basis, the report says that export earnings for the
year of 1997 dropped by 5.6 percent from the previous year.
Earnings from traditional exports decreased to 360.5 million US
dollars from 447.3 million US dollars recorded in the previous
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
