<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WCU Studies SADC Regional Water Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Conservation Union
(WCU) has embarked on a study of water management in the Southern
Africa Development Community (SADC) countries, the WCU said in a
statement released here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
With financial assistance from the Swedish International
Development Agency, the WCU said it was undertaking an 18-month
regional research to investigate and establish water demand
management application in the region.
</P>
<P>
The research would be based on five case studies to be
conducted in South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Mozambique and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The conventional approaches to water management had been to
build elaborate dams to meet the demand for supply, and in
general water had been under-priced, leading often to the abuse
and inefficient use of the resource.
</P>
<P>
Given that supply is likely to be limited, and the building of
dams now becoming an expensive option for countries of the
region, the WCU said there was a need to explore different water
management strategies.
</P>
<P>
The WCU said sustainable water resource management was an
important element of regional security and internal stability and
the region needed to develop effective mechanisms of managing
water.
</P>
<P>
''Water demand is a crucial concern to the countries of the
region because of the increasing human population and associated
demand for resources which require water, especially food,'' the
WCU said.
</P>
<P>
''Some states are already water stressed due to prolonged
droughts or low and unreliable rainfall and while others will
experience water scarcity in the not too distant future,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
The water demand management (WDM) is a management approach
that aims to conserve water by controlling demand.
</P>
<P>
It involves the application of selective economic incentives
to promote efficient and equitable use of water as well as a
number of water conservation measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boxer Chagaev Stripped of World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Ruslan Chagaev, surprise winner
of the world boxing heavyweight title last year, has been stripped
of his gold after being disqualified for being an ineligible
professional.
</P>
<P>
The legal commission of the International Amateur Boxing
Association (AIBA), decided the Uzbek fighter should be suspended
retroactively to October 1997 and must return his gold medal
within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's Felix Savon, who was beaten by Chagaev in the final of
the world championships in Budapest, Hungary last October 25, will
be awarded the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Chagaev outpointed dual Olympic Games gold medallist and
five-time world amateur champion Savon 14-4 in a highly-charged
final. Cuban assistant coach Julian Gonzalez physically attacked
Turkish referee Garip Erkuyumen after the fight.
</P>
<P>
AIBA announced that beaten semi-finalist Mike Hanke of Germany
will be awarded the silver medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
