<HEADLINE> Lithuania, Estonia Become EU's Associated Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The agreements on associated
membership of Lithuania and Estonia in the European Union (EU)
went into effect on February 1, the Interfax news agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two Baltic countries and the EU signed the agreements in
June, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Darius Dehutis, a senior official of Lithuania's Foreign
Ministry, said that the de jure status of Lithuania's associated
member of the EU marks the beginning of a new stage in Lithuania's
integration with the European organization.
</P>
<P>
The EU is opening new opportunities for the movement of goods,
services, capital and workforce with Lithuania, the official added.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, Lithuania actively took part in
multilateral cooperation with the EU. Statistics showed that the
EU accounted for 33 percent of Lithuania's exports before October
1, 1997, while the EU's share in Lithuania's imports stood at 44.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Estonia also regarded the event as an important step to create
conditions for full integration with the European organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
