<HEADLINE> W. Bank Chief Arrives In Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 1 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
Wolfensohn arrived here on Sunday for talks with Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong on the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn, on a swing through Southeast Asia and South Korea
to get a first-hand assessment of the crisis' impact, will meet
with Goh on Monday, the Prime Minister's Office said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"His meeting (with the Prime Minister) is purely to consult
with him. Singapore is not a crisis country and it is an important
regional player," said Graham Barrett, World Bank external affairs
officer for Asia Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn will also meet with representatives from the
corporate and labor sectors of Singapore, as well as other
government officials, a local television report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the rescue packages led by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), the World Bank has pledged 16 billion US dollars to
Asia since July 1997 and has disbursed more than 3.5 billion US
dollars in loans, a statement from the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, which is the least hit by the crisis, has pledged
its assistance in the form of standby loans worth one billion US
dollars to Thailand and five billion US dollars to Indonesia,
under the IMF packages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
