<HEADLINE> Malaysia Rejects Western views on Economic Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has rejected
views by certain Western observers that the economic downturn and
currency crisis faced by Asian countries is due to weak
management, corrupt practices and other negative elements,
according to an official media report.
</P>
<P>
"This outlook suggests that all negative elements are linked to
the East and the West is free from such weaknesses like
safeguarding businesses and cronyism, free from corruption and
social ills," the Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
told reporters Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Hari Raya (Festival of Fast-breaking) open house
at his residence in northern Malaysia, Anwar said if the will is
there among the world community, including the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank, to resolve these
weaknesses, then the community should do so with courage and
determination and not just rely on the developed nations alone,
the Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"They need not hide the fact that inequality and injustices
also occur in the West and they spring from an unfair
international system of trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the West should not deny that injustices favor rich
nations which make use of these to protect their own interests.
</P>
<P>
All factors should be taken into consideration for discussion
on world equality so that a fairer, more accurate discourse could
be reached, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This must be stressed upon because all our statements on
negative elements are related to developing nations. No nation
should be deemed most efficient. All countries should change,
progress and mature," Anwar added.
</P>
<P>
"We should help each other, not out of fear, if we are to have
an environment that is conducive to change," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad had visited Indonesia
and will visit Singapore, the Philippines and Thailand to
formulate a combined strategy to improve the regional economic
situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
