<HEADLINE> Tibet Attracting More Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region attracted a record high 350,000 travelers from
home and overseas last year.
</P>
<P>
The gross earnings for the tourist industry are estimated at
400 million yuan (48.2 million U.S. dollars), including 30 million
U.S. dollars, up 18 percent and 7 percent respectively over
1996. Pre-tax profits are expected to hit 37 million yuan (4.45
million U.S. dollars), up 12 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zhengqi, director of the tourism administrative bureau of
the Tibet Autonomous Region, attributed the increased profit to
the hard work and responsibility of the region's 4,000 staff
members engaged in the travel sector, as well as the economic
growth and social stability in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The local tourism departments intensified their market
promotion activities last year and started to publicize Tibet in
other parts of China and Southeast Asian countries, while
maintaining its traditional European and American markets.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the region established a department to supervise
tourism services, which has been a hit with travelers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
