<HEADLINE> Sign Language to Be Recognized in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Sign language will
receive official recognition in South Africa, thus bringing
official languages in the country to 12, local Sunday Times
reported.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen health workers from hospitals around South Africa are
being trained to use the language.
</P>
<P>
The training is aimed at improving services to disabled
patients who may be misdiagnosed due to communication problems
with doctors or nurses.
</P>
<P>
The pilot project is due to begin tomorrow at the Worcester
Institute for the Deaf in Cape Town, the report said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is a country with many nationalities and tribes.
To cater for diverse peoples in the country, South African
National Assembly adopted in 1996 that 11 languages were the
official languages at national level.
</P>
<P>
The languages are Afrikaans, English, Ndebele, Sepedi, Sesotho
Swati, Xitsonga, Setswana, Tshivenda, Xhosa and Zulu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
