<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Bans Unapproved Trips Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
banned foreign trips by public officers without clearance and
approval of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
The officers are to get the clearance from the office of the
Secretary to the Government of the Federation (SGF) through
written application which should reach the office not less than
three weeks to the departure date.
</P>
<P>
According to a circular signed by the SGF last week, public
officers must get approval from his office in spite of the source
of foreign exchange for the trip.
</P>
<P>
Such application must contain among other things "a clear
statement of the purpose of the trip, the duration and cost
implications" of the journey, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, accounting officers and internal auditors have been
cautioned to ensure compliance with the provisions of the
circular.
</P>
<P>
According to SGF Alhaji Gidado Idris, the government viewed
with serious concern the way and manner ministers and public
servants travel out on frivolous assignments.
</P>
<P>
In the circular, the SGF warned ministers to curb their
overseas travels or face the wrath of government, but he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The allowances given to public officers for their travel
outside the country have been under tense criticism.
</P>
<P>
National Economic Intelligence Committee Chairman Sam Aluko
once disclosed that the officers are paid 360 U.S. Dollars a
night for their stay in foreign countries, which puts Nigeria
next only to the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Even the United Nations and the most developed countries do
not pay that much at public expense, according to him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
