<HEADLINE> China's Non-State Economy Absorbing Surplus Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- China's State Administration
for Industry and Commerce said that its non-state economy has
become an important source of job opportunities for unemployed
state-company workers.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 900,000 workers laid off by state-owned
enterprises found employment with private businesses last year,
and over 1.9 million more jobless workers became self-employed.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, about 55 million Chinese in urban and rural areas were
employed in small businesses, with a total registered capital of
250 billion yuan (30 billion US dollars). The number of private
enterprises increased to 800,000, with more than six million
employees.
</P>
<P>
The non-state economy has become a leading force in the
country's economy, helping maintain a stable social order, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The non-state sector is expected to be able to develop at a
higher rate than the state economy during the 1996-2000 period,
although the state-owned enterprises play a dominant role in
China's economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
