<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China's Shaanxi Using More Direct Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi
Province approved the establishment of 182 direct foreign
investment (DFI) projects in 1997.
</P>
<P>
These projects involved a contractual use of 644 million
U.S. dollars of overseas investment. The province's paid-in sum of
overseas investment for 1997 was 628 million U.S. dollars,
according to an official with the provincial bureau for foreign
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the number of approved DFI projects and
contractual use of overseas investment decreased last year
compared with 1996, but the paid-in volume of foreign investment
increased by 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi is a major scientific and technological research
center, ranking third in the country for its comprehensive
scientific and technological strength.
</P>
<P>
The province has introduced a wide range of measures and
strategies to turn scientific, technological and resource
advantages into economic advantages. It has organized many large
trade and economic activities to publicize the province.
</P>
<P>
It has also attached great importance to the use of overseas
funds and relied on market forces in the use of foreign funds
instead of its past practice of drawing foreign investment only by
offering preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
So far, companies from more than 50 countries and regions,
including Coca Cola of the United States, Rolls Royce of Great
Britain and Siemens of Germany, have invested in the province.
</P>
<P>
The province has approved 2,500 foreign-invested projects which
involve contractual use of more than 4 billion U.S. dollars of
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The actual paid-in sum of overseas investment on these projects
stands at 1.6 billion U.S. dollars, placing the province far ahead
of the neighboring Xinjiang Uygur and Ningxia Hui autonomous
regions as well as Qinghai, Gansu and Shaanxi provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
