<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two New Parties Launched for Cambodia's July Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Two new political parties
were launched simultaneously here Sunday to head into Cambodia's
national elections scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
One of the two parties, named the Reastr Niyum Party, or the
Populationalist Party, was led by First Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Ung Huot.
</P>
<P>
The other was the Sangkum Thmei Party, or the New Society
Party, headed by First Vice Chairman of the National Assembly, or
parliament, Loy Sim Chheang.
</P>
<P>
Their members are from the royalist FUNCINPEC party, which has
been weakened after its leader, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, was
ousted from power in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, son of King Norodom Sihanouk, led the FUNCINPEC to
gain a majority of parliamentary seats in the 1993 national
elections sponsored by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The FUNCINPEC won 58 seats out of a total of 120 in the top
legislature in the 1993 race, while its rival, the Cambodian
People's Party led by Hun Sen, gained 52 seats.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot was elected last August as First Prime Minister to
replace Prince Ranariddh, who has been in exile ever since.
</P>
<P>
Five FUNCINPEC assembly members, including Industry Minister
Pou Sothir and Agriculture Minister Tao Seng Huor, have optioned
to join the Reastr Niyum Party of Ung Huot.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sangkum Thmei Party of Loy Sim Chheang has
recruited five other former FUNCINPEC assembly members.
</P>
<P>
A political analyst here said the formation of the two parties
could be a sign that Prince Ranariddh was losing support from his
party members.
</P>
<P>
The two new parties' leaders were former FUNCINPEC standing
committee members, but were expelled after Prince Ranariddh
declared that they had colluded with Hun Sen's government.
</P>
<P>
Kann Man, a parliamentarian still loyal to Ranariddh, told
Xinhua that the formation of the new parties are only the options
to restore the reputations of their leaders ousted by the
FUNCINPEC.
</P>
<P>
Kann Man added that the two leaders, who used to have dignity
as high officials, wanted to keep up their own choice for stepping
forward in their political lives.
</P>
<P>
About Ung Huot and Loy Sim Chheang's move, Ky Lam Ang, another
FUNCINPEC parliamentarian, said they have rights to form new
parties, so as to avoid being blocked from political activities.
</P>
<P>
Even though some split inside the FUNCINPEC party does exist,
Ky Lam Ang said, the structure of the party is still firm and it
still gains support from the majority of the people.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony for launching his own party, Loy Sim Chheang
argued: "I do not quit from the FUNCINPEC but the leader expelled
me from the party, so I have to go and find a new roof."
</P>
<P>
So far, 41 political parties have been formed to contest in the
coming elections. In comparison, 20 parties were there in the 1993
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
