<BODY>
<HEADLINE> System of Administering Water Resources Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, Feburary 1 (Xinhua) -- China has established a system
of administering water resources, according to reports at a recent
conference on water resources, in Suzhou, in east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
A series of water resource laws and policies have provided
China with 80,000 people in supervisory positions.
</P>
<P>
The rule of law is the basic principle of the Chinese central
government, and senior Water Resource Ministry officials believe
that a fairly complete legal system on water resources will meet
the needs of the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The People's Congress, China's lawmaking body, has passed 70
laws and regulations, and provincial legislatures have approved
some 700 laws, policies and regulations on water resources.
</P>
<P>
In Jiangsu Province, provincial water administration workers
tore down 400 illegal buildings harming water resources protection
in 1997 in related work, and Guangdong Province and the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region have gotten rid of 15,000 sq.m. and
23,000 sq.m. of illegal buildings respectively.
</P>
<P>
Water resource bureaus at all levels have launched a series of
publicity campaigns to enhance public awareness and the idea of
water resources in China to pave the way for a legal system
covering water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
