<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grand Canal Beginning to Attract Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu province
plans to turn the old Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal into a new
tourism site and is preparing a number of activities for tourists
to get in contact with Chinese farmers and enjoy sightseeing on
the canal.
</P>
<P>
To improve services, the local government will build pleasure
boats and train guides and will clear some of the trash along the
canal and plant trees.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Canal, a waterway more than 1,000 miles in length
built in Sui Dynasty (581-618 AD), was one of the two greatest
projects in Chinese history, along with the Great Wall. Now, a
millenium after it was built, the canal is still carrying boats,
but because of silting and pollution, it has lost much of its
former beauty and prominence.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangsu section of the canal passes by economically-booming
cities of Suzhou, Wuxi, Changzhou, and Zhenjiang, and connects
with the Yangtze River, Taihu Lake system, and reaches Hangzhou
and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the province has made an effort to
dredge the section to improve navigation and the canal can handle
500-tonnage boats now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
