<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asian Tourists Flocking to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 120,000 from Southeast Asian
countries flocked to South Korea for skiing in the past 40 days,
up 50 percent from the same period last year, said the Korea
National Tourism Organization Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from the Southeast Asian region,
including from Hong Kong, Taiwan, is increasingly swelling, said
the organization.
</P>
<P>
The state-run tourism body attributed the increasing number to
South Korean won's sharp devaluation against the U.S. dollar,
which has made the nation a competitive tourist spot although the
winter started three weeks later than usual.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1997, South Korea has remained in a serious
financial crisis triggered by the failures of a slew of
conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions, which has
sent the won plunge sharply against the U.S. dollar to new low.
</P>
<P>
Before the crisis, the Greenback equalled some 835 won, but it
has soared to 1,565 against the South Korean currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
