<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changes in Livestock Feed Needed to Ease Grain Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, February 1 (Xinhua) -- An agricultural expert is
calling for changes in animal husbandry which separate food grain
from forage crops.
</P>
<P>
"China's tension over grain shortages will never ease with the
tradition of humans and livestock sharing grain," said Jiang
Yuming, a research fellow from China Rice Research Institute in
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is now focusing on the subject of "how to feed more
people with limited land."
</P>
<P>
He also suggested harvesting forage crops at the end of their
mid-growth period, rather than waiting for crops to mature.
</P>
<P>
Forage crops harvested during this period maintain more
nutrients compared with crops harvested during other periods, he
said.
</P>
<P>
This practice also helps increase the multiple crops index and
makes full use of sunlight and land resources.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the country still follows the old tradition of
feeding livestock with food crops.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the China Forage Office show that 30 percent of
China's grain output, goes to feed livestock every year.
</P>
<P>
With an ever-increasing population and decreasing farmland,
China will begin to face grain shortages in coming years, Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
The improving living standard makes it more difficult, he said,
as China is consuming more and more meat.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, China will produce 170 million tons of forage crops
annually, accounting for 33 percent of the total grain output.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
