<HEADLINE> Neighborhood Committees in China's Urban Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Neighborhood committees in
China's urban areas, or "State Councils" as local residents often
call them, are in contact with as many as 700 households and get
their nickname from their close relations with local residents.
</P>
<P>
China's first neighborhood committee was set up in Shanghai's
Huangpu District in December of 1949, the year new China was
founded, and now there are more than 113,600 of them in urban
areas. The Chinese capital alone had at least 5,000.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guixing, head of a grassroots political power section at
the Beijing Civil Affairs Bureau, said: neighborhood committees
are non-government organizations that play an important role in
maintaining social order and promoting socialist cultural and
ethical progress that can't be done by other government offices.
</P>
<P>
A neighborhood committee consists of six committees in charge
of social order, mediating disputes, social welfare, public
sanitation, family planning, and education.
</P>
<P>
Other tasks include publicizing celebrations of important
events, providing daily help for local residents, or mobilizing
people to kill mice, cockroaches, or mosquitos, according to Wang
Shiliang, director of the Qinan neighborhood committee in
Beijing's Western District.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of some 400,000 people working at
neighborhood committees in China's urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, there are 22,000 people working in local
neighborhood committees, whose heads include retired workers,
laid-off workers, intellectuals, and cadres at various levels,
1,900 of whom have diplomas or are polytechnic school grads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
