<HEADLINE> Li Lanqing: China Should Join WTO at Earliest Possible Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, SWITZERLAND, January 31 (Xinhua) -- China's Vice Premier
Li Lanqing on Saturday expressed his hope that China will join the
World Trade Organization (WTO) at an earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
"Now that major progress has been made in recent negotiations,
we hope the issue will be solved as soon as possible," Li told a
panel session on China Economy of the World Economic Forum meeting.
</P>
<P>
Regarding its entry into the WTO, Li said China has been
working in this direction over the past 11 years, has lowered its
tariff level five times since 1992 and will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
China took part in the entire process of the Uruguay Round of
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) negotiations and
signed the final package agreements with the WTO's predecessor.
</P>
<P>
"The principle for China's entry into the WTO is that China is
ready to undertake the obligations for a developing country and
should at the same time enjoy its due rights," Li stated.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier said he believes the notion that China
needs the WTO and vice versa, adding: "Without China's membership,
the WTO can hardly play a bigger role." 
</P>
</TEXT>
