<HEADLINE> Arafat-Clinton Letter on Covenant Changes Ratified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Council
(PNC) has ratified the letter, which Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat gave to U.S. President Bill
Clinton last month detailing the changes in the Palestinian
Covenant.
</P>
<P>
Arafat convened the 18-member executive committee of the PNC in
the West Bank city of Ramallah Saturday night to discuss the
changed clauses in the covenant calling for Israel's
destruction, Israel Radio reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will consider publishing the amended version of the
covenant after the executive committee ratified the letter,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's communication
adviser David Bar-Illan said that convening the executive
committee is not enough, noting that "canceling the clauses must
be done by the PNC by a two-thirds majority."
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Clinton last month in Washington,
Netanyahu also insisted that the Palestinian Covenant, written
three decades ago, still contains clauses that call for the
destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians contend that those clauses were effectively
nullified by an extraordinary session of the PNC in 1996. But
Israel said the Palestinians had never formally followed up the
pledge to remove the clauses.
</P>
<P>
The Americans have indicated the U.S. administration recognizes
Arafat's letter to Clinton as a fulfillment of the Palestinian
commitment on that issue. And they accept that the drafting of a
new covenant will have to wait for a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
The ratification of the letter came on the eve of the scheduled
meeting on Sunday between Arafat and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who arrived here Saturday night on a visit to
the Middle East region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
