<HEADLINE> All Six Candidates to Race for 2006 Winter Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The field of six candidates for
the 2006 Winter Games will not be reduced to a shortlist of
finalists, according to IOC director General Francois Garrard in
Nagano on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Garrard said that there was no need to repeat the system for
2006 because the number of bids was manageable and all came from
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Recent Olympic elections had 10 or more candidates from several
continents, prompting the IOC to use a "pre-selection" procedure
of manageable and all came from Europe.
</P>
<P>
The six bids submitted to the IOC are: Sion, Switzerland;
Turin, Italy; Zakopane, Poland; Helsinki, Finland, together with
Lillehammer, Norway; and Klagenfurt, Austria, in a three-country
bid with regions of Slovenia and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Carrard said no other bids were expected to be filed by the
expiry of the deadline Sunday night. 
</P>
