<HEADLINE> Albright, Netanyahu Discuss Peace Process, Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Following the talks between
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the U  Albright, who arrived here from London Satu
rday night, headed
immediately into talks with Netanyahu on the Iraqi crisis and the
deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process. The talks were
extended and lasted for five hours till early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Due to the extended talks, Albright canceled a scheduled news
conference Saturday night in the Laromme Hotel and she sent her
spokesman James Rubin to read a statement to the waiting
journalists.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Albright and Netanyahu first dealt with the Iraqi
crisis at the start of their meeting. Albright briefed Netanyahu
about the U.S. plan on handling of the crisis and both leaders
agreed to continue to coordinate closely over the crisis as the
two countries did during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin refused to answer the question if the U.S. accepts
the sovereign right of Israel to retaliate any attack launched by
Iraq. During the Gulf War, Israel was pressured by Washington to
refrain from retaliating the missile attacks by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the two spent most of the time on the issues
concerning the Israeli-Palestinian deadlock, although he cautioned
against an expectation for a quick breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
"Not surprisingly, she (Albright) spent the bulk of the time on
how to break the stalemate between Israelis and Palestinians in
the Middle East peace process. She discussed the ideas that the
president (Bill Clinton) presented to the prime minister
(Netanyahu) and Chairman (Yasser) Arafat and the initial reactions
that both leaders have had to these ideas," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Albright also put forward some new ideas based
on those presented by Clinton during his separate talks with
Netanyahu and Arafat late last month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Albright was refining the Clinton ideas "on a parallel and
step-by-step process where the two sides take spontaneous steps,"
the Palestinians on fighting terror and the Israelis on carrying
out the delayed redeployment in the West Bank, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. and Israel are dealing intensively with the
"quality, quantity and timing of the further redeployment," as
Washington is still pressing Israel to suspend its settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
Albright is to continue talks with Israeli President Ezer
Weizman and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Sunday morning
before travelling to the West Bank city of Ramallah to meet with
Arafat. 
</P>
