<HEADLINE> Minister Complains About Poor Sanitation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Health Minister
Crisplus Kiyonga has complained about poor sanitation in Kampala
and the country, saying that is the reason causing diseases to
rise.
</P>
<P>
He said 30 percent of Kampala resident, or 300,000 people
living in the capital without latrine and have to dispose of
their excreta in polythene bags.
</P>
<P>
Kiyonga revealed the fact last Tuesday at Mulago hospital in
the city where new medical equipment was commissioned.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the country, said the minister, only 4 percent of
residents have their latrines.
</P>
<P>
Cholera was long overdue under such circumstances, he said,
referring to the recent outbreak of the epidemic from last
November to earlier January this year which killed at least 340
Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
Records in 1996 in his ministry said 50 percent of patients
contracted diseases related to poor sanitation, Kiyonga noted.
</P>
<P>
The government has so far spent 27 billions of Uganda
Shillings or 27 millions of U.S. Dollars in the fight against
poor sanitation related diseases, he told the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged health workers to launch an education
program to remind local people to improve their health and
hygienic conditions. It is a pity that 27 billions of Shillings
(some 27 million U.S. Dollars) have been used in fighting
preventive diseases, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
State-owned Mulago hospital has most sophisticated equipment
in the country. The new equipment commissioned includes a central
oxygen/vacuum supply room, a radiotherapy gamma camera room, an
intensive care unit, a radio-pharmacy laboratory and a
computerized tomographic scan.
</P>
<P>
These apparatus were funded by the Ugandan government and the
International Atomic Energy, ''the Monitor'' paper said in a
latest report.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient infrastructure is the problem bothering local
residents and Kampala city council. Infrastructure system in the
city was founded in 1950s when the city had 30,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
