<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Urged to Work Together at Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian Republican Movement
(ARM) chairman Malcolm Turnbull Sunday warned his republican
colleagues to work together to prevent this week's constitutional
convention being used to frustrate progress towards a republic.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters ahead of the start of the convention
Monday, Turnbull also said a deadline for Australia becoming a
republic by the start of the Sydney 2000 Olympics was achievable.
</P>
<P>
"We feel we are getting very close to the time when a
referendum will be put to the Australian people," he said. "It
looks as though that is going to be able to be done, as long as
people working in this convention do so with goodwill."
</P>
<P>
"I said to our colleagues this morning that this convention
cannot create a republic. We can do no more than make a
recommendation to the government and to parliament for a
constitution amendment bill," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "The one thing this convention can do is
delay and frustrate the move to a republic, because if the
delegates ... fail to work in an open-minded constructive fashion
and fail to do the job the Australian people have asked them to
do, then the move to a republic will be delayed."
</P>
<P>
Turnbull said he was hopeful a consensus would be reached at
the conclusion of the two-week convention.
</P>
<P>
"I am highly confident of a consensus being achieved," he said,
adding that under the circumstances, a consensus need only be a
majority of delegates.
</P>
<P>
Turnbull said the ARM continued to oppose a popularly-elected
head of state, preferring a vote by two-thirds majority of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"That would ensure the president had the support of both sides
of politics," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
