<HEADLINE> Zambia's Emergency Law to Affect Aid Inflow: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Association of
Chambers of Commerce and Industry (ZACCI) has said the extension
of the state of emergency will not help the country get the 35
percent of the budget expenditure to be financed by donors.
</P>
<P>
Sunday times paper Sunday quoted ZACCI Chairman George
Chabwera as saying at a budget analysis meeting here Saturday
that the extension of the state of emergency law imposed one day
after the October 28 abortive coup is regrettable as it allegedly
leaves little confidence on the business community.
</P>
<P>
He said since the government expects 35 percent of the 1998
budget to be sourced from the donors, the extension does not give
confidence that the money will be obtained.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Chabwera as further saying that in
1997 Zambia was supposed to get about 210 million U.S. Dollars
from the donors but only about 100 million Dollars was secured.
</P>
<P>
But Finance Minister Ronald Penza defended the extension,
saying that it is necessary to ensure the perpetrators of the
coup attempt are brought to book in time.
</P>
<P>
The issue of good governance is very difficult as this is not
defined and Zambia's cooperating partners can ask for certain
benchmarks but when these are met they raise other issues
relating to the good governance, said Penza, who presented the
1998 budget report last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zambian parliament passed a government motion last Thursday to
extend the state of emergency law for another three months.
</P>
<P>
A total of 95 people have been arrested since the coup
including former president Kenneth Kaunda. Following
international appeals for Kaunda's immediate release or a charge
against him the government transferred Kaunda to under house
arrest on December 31 of 1997 six days after his arrest in
alleged involvement in the coup. 
</P>
