<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korda Wins Australian Open Final (reopen) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The year 1998 is the best year
for Czech tennis star Petr Korda as his dream of becoming a grand
slam champion came true in Melbourne on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 30, he scored an one-sided victory on Sunday over
his opponent in the Australian Open's Final.
</P>
<P>
Sixth-seeded Korda easily beat the error-prone ninth seed
Marcelo Rios of Chile Sunday in straight sets 6-2, 6-2, 6-2 in 82
minutes in the men's final.
</P>
<P>
"I've been waiting for this moment for a long time, it's really
my dream come true," Korda told reporters shortly after the match.
</P>
<P>
After hitting the winning forehand cross-court return past
Rios, Korda sank to his knees and held his head in both hands for
some time.
</P>
<P>
He than hurled his racquet high into the crowd before
scrambling up into the stands to embrace his wife, Regina.
</P>
<P>
Then came his trademark scissors kick after which he pulled his
shirt off and tossed that to the crowd, too.
</P>
<P>
Korda has been popular to spectators and cameramen as he often
do something entertaining on the spot to celebrate his victories.
</P>
<P>
He turned cartwheels on the court after he defeated Karol
Kucera in semi-finals and did scissor jumps in previous victories.
</P>
<P>
With a long-neck and short-cut hair, The skinny and long-limbed
Korda was described in Australia as a human toothbrush.
</P>
<P>
Korda's win was the most one-sided men's Australian final since
Ivan Lendl beat fellow Czech Miloslav Mecir by the same scoreline
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Korda has now vaulted him to number two in the world,
supplanting Australia's Patrick Rafter while Rios has risen to
number five.
</P>
<P>
In his only other grand slam final, Korda lost to American Jim
Courier in the 1992 French Open in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Korda on Sunday earned 405,000 US dollars and Rios took home
202,900 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Korda had an outstanding 1997, winning in Stuttgart and beating
world number one Pete Sampras of the United States in the fourth
round at the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
He is undefeated this year, winning in Qatar a fortnight ago,
and lifting his ranking into the top 10 for the first time in six
years.
</P>
<P>
For most of his career, Korda has languished in mediocrity. In
35 Grand Slam appearances, the left-hander had failed at the first
hurdle 12 times. On the big occasions the Czech used to falter.
</P>
<P>
This is Rios' first Grand Slam final and his third appearance
in the Australian Open. He lost in the first round in 1996 and in
the quarter-finals last year.
</P>
<P>
Rios, 22, said he was disappointed with the loss but had had "a
great week." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
