<HEADLINE> EU Concerned Over Zambia's Extension of State of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
expressed deep concern over Zambia's extension of the state of
emergency for another three months and urged the government to
complete investigations and charge or release all detainees.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Saturday in Lusaka, the EU urged the
Zambian government to investigate the allegations of torture made
by some of the detainees picked up in connection with last year's
abortive October 28 coup, according to Sunday Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union now strongly urges the government of
Zambia to complete their investigations with all possible speed,
to charge or release all the detainees and to end the state of
emergency at the earliest opportunity," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
On the extension of the state of emergency by parliament last
week for another three months, the EU pointed out that it had
hoped the probe into the coup would be completed within the
initial 90 days period of the state of emergency as the extension
would entail continued suspension of basic human rights.
</P>
<P>
However, the state-owned English paper quoted Homes Affairs
Minister Peter Machungwa who defended the parliament's decision
of the extension as saying Saturday that the Zambian government
is responsible for the security of its people and therefore wants
to do a "thorough and professional" job.
</P>
<P>
He added that it is not the wish of the government to delay
the investigation but the limited available resources and the
complexity of the case has caused the extension.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency was declared by President Frederick
Chiluba last October to facilitate the investigations into the
failed coup but it is required to review and ratify by parliament
every three months.
</P>
<P>
Under the state of emergency, more than 90 people including
former president and opposition leader Kenneth Kaunda have been
detained and no one has been tried until now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
