<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korda Wins Australian Open Men's Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The year 1998 is the best year
for 30 year-old Petr Korda as his dream came true Sunday following
his one-sided victory over his opponent in the Australian Open
final.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Korda of Czech Republic easily beat ninth seed
Marcelo Rios of Chile in the men's singles final in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Korda, 30, defeated Rios, 22, in straight sets 6-2, 6-2, 6-2 in
82 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The victory was Korda's second Grand Slam final, having lost to
Jim Courier in Paris in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Korda had an outstanding 1997, winning in Stuttgart and beating
world number one Pete Sampras in the fourth round at the
U. S. Open.
</P>
<P>
He is undefeated this year, winning in Qatar a fortnight ago,
and lifting his ranking into the top 10 for the first time in six
years.
</P>
<P>
For most of his career, Korda has languished in mediocrity. In
35 Grand Slam appearances, the left-hander had failed at the first
hurdle 12 times. On the big occasions the Czech used to falter.
</P>
<P>
This is Rios' first Grand Slam final and his third appearance
in the Australian Open. He lost in the first round in 1996 and in
the quarter-finals last year.
</P>
<P>
Rios had not played a seed on his way to the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
