<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Requests World Bank Loan for Reemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is seeking a 300
million U.S. dollar loan from the World Bank for a program to
create jobs for upcountry workers left unemployed by the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The request was made during talks Saturday between Thai Finance
Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda and World Bank President James
Wolfensohn, who is on a nine-day trip of six Asian countries,
according to the Bangkok Post Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn expressed his full support for the loan request for
a proposed Social Investment Program and expected the World Bank
Board to approve the scheme shortly.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The true impact of crises comes less on the people in
the financial sector, but rather on the millions of people just
near the poverty line."
</P>
<P>
The 300-million dollar Social Investment Program will help
generate jobs in existing projects such as education and tourism.
</P>
<P>
The loan, if approved, will also support rural communities,
possibly including irrigation projects or supporting development
in food processing. Grants or loans would be given to small- and
medium-sized enterprises in upcountry communities, according to
Wolfensohn.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank estimates that 800,000 Thais have already been
left unemployed by the economic crisis. About 10 percent of the
country's 60 million population lives just above the international
poverty line, with daily income of 1-1.5 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has already committed 1.5 billion dollars in
structural adjustment loans to Thailand as part of the 17.2
billion dollar package arranged by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) approved last August.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
