<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Weak on Public Debt, Strong on GDP, Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Italy ranked third in gross
domestic product in 1996 among the 11 European Union countries
groomed for a place in European Monetary Union, and is weak only
in the public debt category, with a debt beyond 120 percent of its
GDP compared with the Maastricht target of 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the midst of talk around Europe on Italy's public finances
and qualifications for the EMU and the single currency, analysts
here noted that Italy, Germany and France together account for
three-quarters of the continent's wealth.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures compiled by the EU statistics office,
Eurostat, for 1996, German GDP ranked first at 1,855 billion ECU,
followed by France at 1,211 billion and Italy at 956 billion.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total GDP of 5,432 billion ECU for the 11 countries,
Germany accounted for 34.14 percent, France for 22.2 percent and
Italy for 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Italy's national debt in 1996 came to 1,184 billion ECU
for 28.9 percent of its total debt, said the analysts. The French
debt weighed in at only 16.4 percent at 671.5 billion ECU, and
Spain's came to 323 billion ECU for 7.9 percent of its total.
</P>
<P>
As for balances of trade, the figures for October last year,
the latest available, show a surplus for Italy of 22.6 billion
ECU, more than triple Germany's surplus of 6.6 billion and
eightfold France's 2.78 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Bosnian Serb government Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The new Bosnian Serb
government headed by Milorad Dodik was sworn in on Saturday at a
ceremony held at a parliament session in the western town of Banja
Luka.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to parliament after the inaugural ceremony, Prime
Minister Dodik said his government will work hard for the
prosperity of the republic with the support of all the people and
parties in the republic and the support from international
communities.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Serb president Biljana Plavsic and Hanns Schumacher,
deputy to Bosnia's top international official, were present
during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The new government, which was nominated by president Plavsic
and has pledged to implement the 1995 Dayton peace accords, was
appointed on January 18 by the Bosnian Serb parliament after a
walk-out by ultra-nationalist members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav News Agency reported the ultranationalist deputies
of the Serb Democratic party left the session before the ceremony
began.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday the Bosnia Serb parliament adopted a
government proposal to move the seat of government from the
hardliners' stronghold in Pale to Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
It also cancelled 33 laws, concerning defense, the army and the
interior ministry, that were promulgated by the former
legislature, which had continued to meet despite its dissolution
by Plavsic last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
