<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Burnt to Death in Van Crash in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Eight people were burnt to
death in Malaysia when the van they were traveling in skidded and
crashed into the divider on the North-South Highway near a toll
plaza south of here early Sunday morning, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Two other occupants of the van, a man and a baby, survived the
crash which occurred at about 3:50 a.m. and have been admitted to
a hospital in Seremban, about 65 kilometers south of here, with
their condition still unknown, the reports said quoting police.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the van, which was heading towards Johor
Baharu, some 370 kilometers southeast from here, caught fire after
it skidded and crashed into the divider at the point of 258.9
kilometers along the North-South Highway.
</P>
<P>
The number of fatalities in the crash, whose cause is yet to be
known, is the largest in a single accident since Statistics
Operation was launched 11 days ago to prevent road accidents
during the double celebrations of Chinese Lunar New Year and Hari
Raya (Muslims' Festival of Fast-breaking) which fell on January 28
and January 30 respectively.
</P>
<P>
By Saturday, the second day of Hari Raya, when 25 people were
killed, a total of 203 people had lost their lives in road
accidents during the Operation, the Malaysian Police headquarters
here said in a statement Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IJO Approves Scientific Jute Cultivation Work Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 1 (Xinhua) -- The Dhaka-based International
Jute Organization (IJO) has approved a work plan for scientific
jute cultivation in jute-growing countries for producing quality
jute, an IJO source said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The IJO has also launched a 400,000 U.S. dollar project for
introducing the newly-evolved jute varieties and jute-related farm
technologies to the growers, the source added.
</P>
<P>
The work plan for jute promotion was approved at a two-day IJO
session on the project late last month.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to continue all breeding activities and
related trials initiated under the project in order to release
suitable varieties at the national level as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
In the work plan, jute experts suggested identifying the most
suitable varieties, farmers and farmer groups, technologies and
cropping patterns for adaptive research trials and demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The experts also suggested that jute-growing training be
conducted through field trials, and dissemination work of the
jute-growing knowledge should include cultivation practices,
production of quality seeds and fibers, processing and seed
storing, grading and fiber storing.
</P>
<P>
Initiated early this year and funded by the Rome-based
International Fund for Agricultural Development, the project is
scheduled for completion at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The project, apart from boosting jute and kenaf production, is
also expected to help generate income for the farmers through
application of improved technology.
</P>
<P>
The research systems of the project-participating countries --
Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Nepal and Thailand -- will
collaborate with the IJO in implementing the project, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
The IJO was established in January 1984 with its headquarters
in Dhaka, under the integrated program for commodities for the
United Nations Conference on Trade and Development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
