<HEADLINE> Dini Urges More Diplomacy to End Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 31 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini urged Saturday a further push in diplomatic efforts to
resolve the crisis over U,N. arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Not all the diplomatic avenues have been fully explored yet, "
he said, "even though recent developments have created a situation
of grave difficulty in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said Friday "force may
have to be used as a last resort" in the ongoing confrontation
with the Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was "foolhardy" of Saddam to continue refusing
access of U.N. inspectors to suspected chemical and biological
weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
In recent days the United States has warned that it too is
prepared to use force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to Dini, Washington is "in constant contact with
other countries" on the subject of the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
He himself would be in contact with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright later Saturday to "give her our opinion, which,
I repeat, is that a diplomatic solution must be found," said
Dini.
</P>
<P>
Asked what Italy's attitude would be if diplomatic channels
were unfruitful, Dini said, "We'll cross that bridge when we come
to it. We are not there yet and I hope we won't get there. "
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
