<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
--The leading national newspaper has a frontpage report on
high-tech products responding to the law of the marketplace in
Beijing as the local government tries to give a helping hand to
adjusting the product mix.
</P>
<P>
It says that 100 professors from Qinghua University have
prepared scientific and technological projects in cooperation with
manufacturers in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
-- Qiao Shi, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC), has urged Shenzhen in Guangdong
Province to explore construction efforts further.
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit to the special economic zone, Qiao
said that because the 21st century is approaching government
should do strategic studies of projects that can help social and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
-- The Mianyang National High-Tech New Technology Industrial
Development Zone in China's Sichuan Province is now home to 754
enterprises involved in industrial applications of electronic and
information technologies, new materials and fine chemicals. It
generated 12 billion yuan in earnings last year.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
--The economic development zone along the Yangtze, with
Shanghai at its head, has played an important role in the Yangtze
River and Yangtze Delta development, since being designated an
open area six years ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing arrived in Davos on Saturday for the
1998 meeting of the World Economic Forum (WEF).
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Li will meet with world political and business
leaders, including United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Swiss President Flavio Cotti, WEF Chairman Klaus Schwab, and World
Trade Organization Director-General Renato Ruggiero.
</P>
<P>
 "China Youth Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The newspaper has photos of sailors and officers on a
destroyer on the Yellow Sea spending this year's Spring Festival
watching fireworks from a nearby city, making jiaozi, and
providing cultural programs. Some officers took their turn on duty
so that the sailors could watch the cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Merchants International Tourism Corporation, which
has six travel agencies, was recently given a certificate of
quality for the International Standardization Organization (ISO)
by the China National Tourism Administration and the China
National Bureau for Technical Supervision.
</P>
<P>
China now has over 2,000 travel agencies providing domestic and
international tourism services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
