<HEADLINE> Rapid Growth And High Returns For Pudong's Foreign-funded Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 1 (Xinhua) -- Large foreign-funded
industrial projects in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai have one of
the fastest growth rates and highest returns in China, market
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
A recent study of 157 industrial projects since the Pudong New
Area was opened to attract foreign investment seven years ago,
each with at least 10 million US dollars in investment, found that
73.9 percent were operational. The projects took an average of
17.2 months to build, which is considered efficient by experts.
</P>
<P>
A 410-million-US-dollar Sino-Japanese color television project,
for example, produced its first color TV 18 months after
construction work started.
</P>
<P>
The projects now in operation have also proven profitable, with
80 percent already generating a profit.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of 50 million US dollars, Shanghai-Hitachi
Electrical, began production within a year of start of
construction, 11 months ahead of schedule, so the Japanese decided
to add another 80 million US dollars of investment. Because the
construction work was faster than in Japan for a similar-size
project, Japanese investors dubbed it "Pudong speed and Pudong
efficiency."
</P>
<P>
Last year, 10 multinationals added 255 million US dollars in
investment, and market analysts attribute this to the good
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the 157 projects surveyed are in
high-tech manufacturing funded by leading multinationals.
</P>
<P>
A "Brand-name strategy" has also contributed to the success. Of
the 52 foreign brands and 50 Chinese in production, 25 foreign
brands and 17 Chinese have a good share of the market both in and
outside China.
</P>
<P>
A program-controlled telephone switchboard produced by the
Sino-Belgian Shanghai-Bell has more than 45 percent of the China
market. Its price per telephone line is less than 100 US dollars,
compared with 260 US dollars for some foreign-made products in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
