<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Stabilize Money Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior Myanmar finance
official has stressed the need to stabilize the country's money
market in the wake of the regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of a private branch bank here Saturday,
U Khin Maung Thein, minister for finance and revenue, emphasized
that the country must overcome the unscrupulous persons'
subversive acts of spreading rumors to destabilize its money
market, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar must be well prepared for a worse scenario though the
current Asian financial crisis affected the country just a
little, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The market exchange rate of Myanmar currency kyat against the
U.S. dollar once fell to as low as 380 last November-December
when it was hit by regional currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate has improved following the cracking down by
the authorities on illegal currency trading since the beginning
of January, maintaining at about 270 kyats per dollar now.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, the minister also called for
improvement of banking services through innovation and
cooperation with fellow members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
There are 25 private banks and 48 foreign bank representative
offices in Myanmar in addition to six state-owned banks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
