<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, January 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are some of
the major economic news items from the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) countries in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay's Cotton Output to Be Doubled in 1998
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Paraguay's cotton production in 1998 will double
that of 1997 to 300,000 gross tons, which is to be the first
increase in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Due to bad weather and low prices on the international market,
the country's cotton production suffered reduction for years.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the government started to provide technical assistance
and fertilizers to small producers, which helped increase the area
of cultivation and the yield per hectare.
</P>
<P>
Creating some 500,000 jobs and bringing hard currency into the
country, cotton is one of the pillar economies in Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
Chile's Overseas Investment Increases
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's total overseas investment in 1997 was up 123
percent to 2.248 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, the United States, the Cayman Islands and Uruguay
are the top four countries which attracted most of Chile's
investors.
</P>
<P>
Sectors that received the highest share of Chilean capital
were finances, insurance and goods and services, which totalled
1.461 billion dollars, followed by the manufacturing industry,
mining and commerce.
</P>
<P>
Brazil to Export 310,000 Tons of Meat in 1998
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian meat exports in 1998 will grow by 10
percent to 310,000 tons, valued at 460 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country will seek to export more meat to Japan and Russia,
besides its traditional markets.
</P>
<P>
Argentina to Get Loan From IMF
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina will sign a loan agreement with the
International Monetary Fund, under which Argentina will get a
2.8-billion-dollar loan from the financial organization during the
next three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
