<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Lanqing: China Should Join WTO at Earliest Possible Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, SWITZERLAND, January 31 (Xinhua) -- China's Vice Premier
Li Lanqing on Saturday expressed his hope that China will join the
World Trade Organization (WTO) at an earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
"Now that major progress has been made in recent negotiations,
we hope the issue will be solved as soon as possible," Li told a
panel session on China Economy of the ongoing annual meeting of
the World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
Regarding its entry into WTO, Li recalled, China has been
working in this direction over the past 11 years. China took part
in the entire process of the Uruguay Round of GATT negotiations
and signed the final package agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1992, China has lowered its tariff level five times and
will continue to do so, although it is still not a WTO member," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The principle for China's entry into WTO is that China is
ready to undertake the obligations for a developing country and
should at the same time enjoy its due rights," Li stated.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that China needs WTO and vice versa,
adding, "Without China's membership, WTO can hardly play a bigger
role." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
