<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Premier Reiterates China's Will to Keep RMB Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, SWITZERLAND, January 31 (Xinhua) -- China will keep its
currency RMB stable despite the financial turmoil in many of the
Asian countries and at the same time achieve an eight-percent
growth of its GDP, China's Vice Premier Li Lanqing said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Li was speaking at a panel session on China Economy in the Davos
Congress Center, where the 1998 annual meeting of the World Economic
Forum is going on.
</P>
<P>
"This year, while ensuring a stable RMB, we will adopt various
sound and effective policies and measures to achieve eight percent
of growth of our GDP," Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
China's GDP in 1997 increased 8.8 percent with inflation at 0.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
"Through years of reform, we have found an operation model for
our macro economy, an economy with high growth and low inflation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Li told the session that China, though till now has not been
directly affected, has prepared itself for the possible impact and
worked out counter measures.
</P>
<P>
He assured that China will not slow down its reform,
especially reform of its financial system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
