<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: US Attacks Would Not Destroy Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said today that any U.S. military attack on Iraq
would be "significant" but would not aim to destroy the country
and topple President Saddam Hussein from power.
</P>
<P>
"Let's not raise unreasonable expectations," Cohen told
reporters at the Pentagon. "We do not have as a goal the toppling
of Saddam Hussein."
</P>
<P>
He said the purpose of military attacks on Iraq would be to
devastate Saddam's ability to make chemical or biological weapons
or threaten his neighbors, but not devastate Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said diplomatic efforts were still under way to get
Baghdad to accept unfettered U.N. inspections for chemical and
biological weapons. And he said no attack decision had been made.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to visit Saudi Arabia and other Gulf states next
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
