<DOCNO> XIE19980201.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-31 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Arrives in Israel on Mideast Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright arrived here Saturday evening from London for
a whirlwind visit apparently with primary objectives to nudge
Israeli and Palestinian leaders into peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after her arrival, Albright immediately entered into
talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the
later's Jerusalem residence.
</P>
<P>
The projected Israel's troop redeployment in the West Bank
will dominate this round of discussion, but Albright will also
update Netanyahu on the scope of the impending U.S. military
strikes against Iraq and to coordinate in the event that Israel
is drawn into the theater of operations, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has not made its final decision on
the scope of troop redeployment since the Washington talks held
last week, which is one of the biggest issue hindering the
peace talks right now.
</P>
<P>
During the Washington talks with netanyahu and U.S. President
Bill Clinton was in favor of Netanyahu's proposal that Israel
implements partial and gradual troop pullbacks in the West Bank,
should the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) fulfill its
obligations of the signed accords.
</P>
<P>
But PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat, upon his return from Egypt
on Tuesday, rejected this proposal, saying he "would definitely
not agree" to such an idea.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to hold talks on Sunday with Arafat
in Ramallah, the PNA controlled West bank city.
</P>
<P>
Besides asking Arafat to make more compromise in reviving
the peace talks, Albright's talks with Arafat is likely
to touch on the PNA's public support of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
